@*
    Example 5 — Driving the control from your own UI.

    Sometimes you want bigger, more discoverable affordances than a
    dropdown — an A- / A+ pair in a settings page, say. SetSizeAsync
    applies a size imperatively through a @ref, so your own buttons run
    the same lifecycle the listbox does: data-text-size is set,
    localStorage is written, OnChange and ValueChanged fire.

    TextSizeChooser.SizeName is exported for exactly this reason: your own
    UI can render labels that match the listbox without duplicating the
    title-casing rule.

    Note the aria-pressed on each preset button — these are toggles, and
    the state must be readable by assistive technology, not just visible
    as a highlight (WCAG 1.4.1: no colour-only meaning).
*@

@page "/examples/text-size-chooser/external-buttons"
@rendermode InteractiveServer
@using LilyDesignSystem.Blazor.Helpers

<TextSizeChooser
    @ref="picker"
    Label="Text size"
    Sizes="@Sizes"
    StorageKey="lily-text-size"
    @bind-Value="size" />

<div role="group" aria-label="Text size presets">
    @foreach (var slug in Sizes)
    {
        <button type="button"
                aria-pressed="@(slug == size ? "true" : "false")"
                @onclick="() => picker!.SetSizeAsync(slug)">
            @TextSizeChooser.SizeName(slug)
        </button>
    }
</div>

<p class="text-size-chooser-status" aria-live="polite">
    Text size: @(string.IsNullOrEmpty(size) ? "none" : TextSizeChooser.SizeName(size))
</p>

@code {
    private static readonly string[] Sizes =
        new[] { "small", "medium", "large", "x-large" };

    private TextSizeChooser? picker;
    private string size = "";
}
